 Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Dubhghaill</b> ‘son of <i>Dubhghall</i>’, a byname meaning ‘dark stranger’, used among the Gaels to distinguish the darker-haired Danes from fair-haired Norwegians. This is the usual Irish spelling of this name, while   McDougall   is the usual Scottish spelling. However,   McDowall   is also common in south west Scotland and a prominent Galloway family with this name first appear in the historical record in the late 13th century."],"variants":[{"name":"McDougall","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Dubhghaill</b>, ‘son of <i>Dubhghall</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>dubh</i> ‘black’ + <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’. This was originally a byname used to distinguish the darker-haired Danes from the fair-haired Norwegians. Compare   McDowell   and   Doyle  ."]},{"name":"Madill","meanings":["Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of   McDowell  .","Scottish: variant of   McDill  ."]},{"name":"McDole","meanings":["Irish: variant of   McDowell  ."]},{"name":"Madole","meanings":["Irish (northern): shortened form of   McDowell  ."]},{"name":"McDill","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   McDowell  ."]},{"name":"McCool","meanings":["Irish (northern): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Comhghaill</b> ‘son of the servant (i.e. devotee) of (Saint) <i>Comhghall</i>’, a personal name, possibly an intensive of <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’, borne by an early Irish saint.","Irish (northern) and Manx: possibly an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Dhubhghaill</b>. See   McDowell  ."]},{"name":"McDowall","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scottish Alasdair.","Scottish and Irish: variant of   McDowell  ."]}]},{"name":"Kathleen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Irish origin: traditional Anglicized form of   Caitlín ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kathlene","meanings":["Of Irish o